Predicting Personal Loan Acceptance for Universal Bank

This project uses customer demographic and financial data from Universal Bank to build machine learning models that predict whether a customer will accept a personal loan offer.

Section 1 Project Overview

1.1 Dataset and Problem Description

  • Indicate which dataset you selected (name and source).
  • Dataset Name: Universal Bank Personal Loan Dataset
  • Source: Kaggle Bank Personal Loan Machine Learning Project
  • Describe the size of the dataset (number of rows and columns).
  • Number of rows (observations): 5,012
  • Number of columns (variables): 12
  • Introduce all variables: provide a short description of each key variable and its meaning.
  • Age: Customers age (in years)
  • Experience: Number of years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousands)
  • Family: Family size (1 = single, 2 = married couple, etc.)
  • CCAvg: Average monthly spending on credit cards (in thousands)
  • Education: Education level (1 = Undergraduate, 2 = Graduate, 3 = Advanced/Professional)
  • Mortgage: Value of mortgage if any (in thousands)
  • Personal_Loan: Target variable whether the customer accepted the personal loan offer (1 = Yes, 0 = No)
  • Securities_Account: Whether the customer has a securities account with the bank (1 = Yes, 0 = No)
  • CD_Account: Whether the customer holds a certificate of deposit account (1 = Yes, 0 = No)
  • Online: Whether the customer uses online banking services (1 = Yes, 0 = No)
  • CreditCard: Whether the customer has a credit card issued by the bank (1 = Yes, 0 = No)

1.2 Business Motivation

  • What is the business problem you are trying to solve?

Universal Bank is a financial institution that offers various services such as savings accounts, credit cards, and investment products.
To increase revenue and strengthen customer relationships, the bank recently launched a personal loan marketing campaign.
However, only a small portion of customers accepted the offer, suggesting that the campaign may not have effectively reached the right audience. The business goal is to identify which customers are most likely to accept a personal loan offer based on their demographic and financial characteristics.
By accurately predicting loan acceptance, the bank can:

  • Improve the efficiency of future marketing campaigns.
  • Reduce unnecessary marketing costs.
  • Better understand the behavioral patterns of high-value customers.
  • Enhance overall customer targeting and relationship management.
  • Who are the stakeholders involved (e.g., managers, teams, customers)?

Marketing Managers:
Responsible for designing and executing personal loan campaigns.
They will use the models predictions to identify high-potential customers and optimize marketing budgets.

Product and Retail Banking Teams:
Oversee customer relationship management and cross-selling strategies.
They can use insights to refine product positioning and improve customer engagement.

Data Analytics / Data Science Team:
Develop, validate, and maintain predictive models.
They ensure the analysis is accurate, interpretable, and aligned with business goals.

Senior Management / Executives:
Use model insights to make strategic decisions about marketing investments and customer segmentation.

Customers:
Indirect stakeholders who benefit from more relevant and personalized offers rather than generic promotions.

  • What are the potential benefits or costs of not solving this problem?

Potential Benefits:

  • Improved marketing efficiency: The bank can focus its campaigns on customers most likely to accept the personal loan offer.
  • Reduced acquisition costs: Fewer resources wasted on uninterested customers, improving return on marketing investment (ROI).
  • Enhanced customer relationships: More relevant and personalized offers increase satisfaction and long-term loyalty.
  • Data-driven decision-making: Provides measurable insights that can guide future product launches and targeting strategies.

Potential Costs of Not Solving the Problem:

  • Inefficient marketing campaigns: Continued spending on broad, untargeted offers with low conversion rates.
  • Lost revenue opportunities: Missing out on customers who are likely to accept loans but were not properly identified.
  • Customer fatigue: Overexposing uninterested customers to irrelevant promotions, potentially harming brand perception.
  • Competitive disadvantage: Other banks using analytics may outperform Universal Bank in customer acquisition and retention.

# === Check for missing values ===
print("\n=== Missing Values ===")
missing_counts = df.isna().sum()
if missing_counts.sum() > 0:
    print("Columns with missing values:")
    print(missing_counts[missing_counts > 0])
    print("\nRemoving rows with missing values...")
    df = df.dropna()  # remove rows with missing values
    print(f"Missing values removed. New dataset shape: {df.shape}")
else:
    print("No missing values found.")
print("\n" + "-"*50)

# === Check for duplicate rows ===
print("\n=== Duplicate Rows ===")
num_duplicates = df.duplicated().sum()
print(f"Number of duplicate rows: {num_duplicates}")

if num_duplicates > 0:
    print("Removing duplicate rows...")
    df = df.drop_duplicates()
    print(f"Duplicates removed. New dataset shape: {df.shape}")
else:
    print("No duplicate rows found.")
print("\n" + "-"*50)


# === Check for impossible or out-of-range values ===
print("\n=== Check for Impossible or Out-of-Range Values ===")

if 'Age' in df.columns:
    invalid_age = df[df['Age'] < 0]
    print(f"Invalid ages found: {len(invalid_age)}")
    if len(invalid_age) > 0:
        df = df[df['Age'] >= 0]
        print("Negative ages removed.")
else:
    print("No Age column found.")

if 'Income' in df.columns:
    invalid_income = df[df['Income'] < 0]
    print(f"Invalid income values found: {len(invalid_income)}")
    if len(invalid_income) > 0:
        df = df[df['Income'] >= 0]
        print("Negative income values removed.")
else:
    print("No Income column found.")
print("\n" + "-"*50)

# === Detect potential outliers (numeric columns only) ===
print("\n=== Outlier Detection (IQR Method) ===")
numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns

for col in numeric_cols:
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outlier_count = df[(df[col] < lower_bound) | (df[col] > upper_bound)].shape[0]
    if outlier_count > 0:
        print(f"{col}: {outlier_count} potential outliers")
print("\n" + "-"*50)


print("\nData Quality Check and Basic Cleaning Completed.")
print(f"Final dataset shape: {df.shape}")

2.4 Insights

In this section, summarize what you discovered from your data exploration (Section 2.3).
Your goal is to translate observations into insights that connect back to your business question.

What are the 24 most important insights you found?

  1. Income and credit card spending (CCAvg) are key differentiators.
    Customers with higher income and greater monthly credit card spending are much more likely to accept a personal loan. These features show the strongest relationship with the target variable Personal Loan.

  2. Education level influences loan acceptance.
    Customers with graduate or professional degrees tend to have higher income, higher credit card usage, and a higher loan acceptance rate. Education likely acts as a proxy for financial stability and openness to financial products.

  3. Financial indicators are interrelated.
    Income, credit card spending, and mortgage value are positively correlated indicating that higher-income customers also tend to have higher assets and spending capacity.

  4. Several variables are right-skewed with outliers.
    Variables such as CCAvg, Mortgage, and Income_per_member show strong right skewness. A few customers spend or earn far more than the rest, suggesting the need for log transformations or outlier handling before modeling.

  5. Demographic segments differ in behavior.
    Older customers and those with larger families are slightly more likely to accept personal loans, while younger customers or single individuals show lower acceptance rates.

Which variables seem most influential or interesting?

  • Income, CCAvg, and Education appear to be the most influential predictors.
  • Family size and Age add demographic depth but show weaker direct influence.
  • The derived variable Income_per_member also provides a more precise measure of household financial capacity.

Did you notice any unexpected relationships or trends?

  • Despite expectations, not all high-income customers accepted the loan suggesting that income alone is not sufficient; marketing communication or risk perception might also play a role.
  • Mortgage showed limited direct correlation with loan acceptance, which may indicate that customers already carrying debt are less interested in new loans.
  • Education seems to drive acceptance more strongly than Age, highlighting that knowledge and financial literacy may be stronger predictors than demographic maturity.

What do these findings imply for business decisions?

  • The bank can target marketing efforts toward high-income, high-spending, and well-educated customers to increase acceptance rates.
  • Campaign messaging could emphasize financial flexibility and tailored loan offers rather than basic credit availability.
  • Customer segmentation based on spending behavior and education may improve marketing ROI.

# ============================================================
# 4.1 Modeling Setup
# ============================================================

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# 4.1.1 Task Type
# ------------------------------------------------------------
# This is a **supervised classification** task.
# Target variable (y): "Personal Loan"  indicates whether a customer accepted
# the banks personal loan offer (1 = Yes, 0 = No).
# Goal: Predict which customers are most likely to accept the offer.
#
# Why this approach fits:
# - The target variable is known and binary  classification is appropriate.
# - Predicting customer acceptance helps marketing managers identify
#   high-potential customers and reduce campaign costs.
# ------------------------------------------------------------

# Define target and features
target = "Personal Loan"
X = df.drop(columns=[target])
y = df[target]

print("Task Type: Supervised Classification")
print(f"Target variable: {target}")
print(f"Shape of X: {X.shape}")
print(f"Shape of y: {y.shape}")
print("\n" + "-"*50)


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# 4.1.2 Feature Selection
# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Selected key features (independent variables):
#   - Income: indicator of financial capacity.
#   - CCAvg: monthly average credit card spending, proxy for spending behavior.
#   - Education: level of financial literacy and earning potential.
#   - Family: household size, may affect borrowing needs.
#   - Age: stage in career and financial life cycle.
#   - Mortgage: existing home loan amount.
#   - Securities Account / CD Account / Online / CreditCard: reflect product
#     engagement and digital behavior with the bank.
#
# Rationale:
# - These variables capture both financial status and customer engagement.
# - Demographic + behavioral features together improve prediction accuracy.
# ------------------------------------------------------------

selected_features = [
    "Age",
    "Experience",
    "Income",
    "Family",
    "CCAvg",
    "Education",
    "Mortgage",
    "Securities Account",
    "CD Account",
    "Online",
    "CreditCard",
    "Income_per_member",
    "log_CCAvg"
]

X = df[selected_features]
print("Selected Features for Modeling:")
for f in selected_features:
    print("-", f)
print("\n" + "-"*50)


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# 4.1.3 Data Splitting or Sampling
# ------------------------------------------------------------
# We'll divide the dataset into training and testing sets for fair evaluation.
# - 80% of the data used for training the models.
# - 20% reserved for testing (unseen data).
# - random_state ensures reproducibility.
#
# Note: Because the target is binary, stratify=y keeps class balance in both sets.
# ------------------------------------------------------------

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(

)

# =============================================================
# SECTION 3.2  Naive Models and Evaluation
# Model 1: K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
# Model 2: Random Forest
# =============================================================

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import (
    accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score,
    f1_score, roc_auc_score, classification_report,
    confusion_matrix
)

sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.rcParams.update({"figure.figsize": (8,4)})

results = []

# -------------------------------------------------------------
# ===================== MODEL 1  KNN =========================
# -------------------------------------------------------------
print("\n" + "="*65)
print("MODEL 1  K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)")
print("="*65 + "\n")

# 1 TRAINING
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
knn.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
print(" Model trained (k = 5)\n")

# 2 EVALUATION
y_pred_knn = knn.predict(X_test_scaled)
y_proba_knn = knn.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:,1]

acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_knn)
prec = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_knn, zero_division=0)
rec = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_knn, zero_division=0)
f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_knn, zero_division=0)
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_knn)

print(" KNN Evaluation Metrics")
print(f"Accuracy : {acc:.4f}")
print(f"Precision: {prec:.4f}")
print(f"Recall   : {rec:.4f}")
print(f"F1 score : {f1:.4f}")
print(f"ROC AUC  : {auc:.4f}\n")

print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_knn, zero_division=0))

#  Confusion Matrix Visualization
cm_knn = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_knn)
plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
sns.heatmap(cm_knn, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['Pred: No Loan', 'Pred: Loan'],
            yticklabels=['Actual: No Loan', 'Actual: Loan'])
plt.title("KNN Confusion Matrix")
plt.ylabel("Actual")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 3 SMALL EXPERIMENT  Effect of k on accuracy
k_values = range(1, 21)
acc_list = []
for k in k_values:
    model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    acc_list.append(accuracy_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test_scaled)))

plt.plot(k_values, acc_list, marker='o')
plt.title("KNN Accuracy vs k (Number of Neighbors)")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

best_k = k_values[int(np.argmax(acc_list))]
print(f"Naive scan  best k  {best_k}, accuracy = {max(acc_list):.4f}\n")

# 4 RECORD RESULTS
results.append({
    "Model": "KNN",
    "Notes": f"k=5 baseline; best_k{best_k}",
    "Accuracy": acc, "Precision": prec, "Recall": rec, "F1": f1, "ROC_AUC": auc
})


# -------------------------------------------------------------
# ================== MODEL 2  Random Forest ==================
# -------------------------------------------------------------
print("\n" + "="*65)
print("MODEL 2  Random Forest")
print("="*65 + "\n")

# 1 TRAINING
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(" Model trained (100 trees)\n")

# 2 EVALUATION
y_pred_rf = rf.predict(X_test)
y_proba_rf = rf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

acc_rf = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_rf)
prec_rf = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_rf, zero_division=0)
rec_rf = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_rf, zero_division=0)
f1_rf = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_rf, zero_division=0)
auc_rf = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_rf)

print(" Random Forest Evaluation Metrics")
print(f"Accuracy : {acc_rf:.4f}")
print(f"Precision: {prec_rf:.4f}")
print(f"Recall   : {rec_rf:.4f}")
print(f"F1 score : {f1_rf:.4f}")
print(f"ROC AUC  : {auc_rf:.4f}\n")

print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_rf, zero_division=0))

#  Confusion Matrix Visualization
cm_rf = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_rf)
plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
sns.heatmap(cm_rf, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Greens', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['Pred: No Loan', 'Pred: Loan'],
            yticklabels=['Actual: No Loan', 'Actual: Loan'])
plt.title("Random Forest Confusion Matrix")
plt.ylabel("Actual")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 3 SMALL EXPERIMENT  Feature Importance + Tree Depth Distribution
fi = pd.Series(rf.feature_importances_, index=X.columns).sort_values(ascending=False)
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.barplot(x=fi.values[:10], y=fi.index[:10], palette="viridis")
plt.title("Random Forest  Top 10 Feature Importances")
plt.xlabel("Importance")
plt.ylabel("Feature")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

tree_depths = [estimator.tree_.max_depth for estimator in rf.estimators_]
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.histplot(tree_depths, bins=10, kde=False, color="green")
plt.title("Distribution of Tree Depths in Random Forest")
plt.xlabel("Tree Depth")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 4 RECORD RESULTS
results.append({
    "Model": "Random Forest",
    "Notes": "100 trees baseline; importance + tree depth plotted",
    "Accuracy": acc_rf, "Precision": prec_rf, "Recall": rec_rf, "F1": f1_rf, "ROC_AUC": auc_rf
})

display(results_df)

plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))

    data=results_df.reset_index(),

    hue="Model", palette="viridis", legend=False
)

3.3 Model Comparisons & Interpretation

Which model performed better overall, and why?

The Random Forest model clearly outperformed the K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) model across all metrics.

  • Random Forest achieved an accuracy of 0.994, F1 = 0.968, and ROC AUC = 0.9997, compared with KNNs accuracy of 0.944, F1 = 0.636, and ROC AUC = 0.946.
  • The ensemble approach helped Random Forest capture complex nonlinear relationships and interactions among features, leading to much higher recall (0.95 vs 0.51) and overall predictive power.

Did any feature show a strong influence on the prediction?

  • Feature-importance plots from the Random Forest revealed that Income, CCAvg (credit-card spending), and Education were the three most influential predictors of loan acceptance.
  • These variables reflect both customers financial capability and spending behavior, aligning well with business intuition: wealthier, higher-spending, and better-educated clients are more likely to accept a personal-loan offer.

Were there trade-offs (e.g., interpretability vs accuracy)?

  • The Random Forest provided far better accuracy but at the cost of interpretability, since its predictions come from hundreds of decision trees that are difficult to visualize as explicit rules.
  • The KNN model, while simple and more transparent conceptually, struggled to generalize to complex patterns and was sensitive to scaling and choice of k.

Note any limitations, surprises, or ideas for improvement.

  • Limitations: Both models were trained on historical data from a single bank; external validity may be limited. Random Forest could still overfit slightly without cross-validation or pruning.
  • Surprises: KNNs recall was quite low despite decent accuracy, meaning it missed many true loan acceptors.
  • Ideas for improvement: Try hyperparameter tuning (e.g., n_estimators, max_depth), test additional ensemble methods such as Gradient Boosting / XGBoost, and address class imbalance through stratified sampling or resampling techniques.

Section 4 Executive Summary & Business Implications

4.1 Main Findings

The Random Forest model outperformed KNN and proved highly accurate ( 99% accuracy, ROC AUC 1.00) in predicting which Universal Bank customers are most likely to accept a personal-loan offer.
Key drivers of loan acceptance were Income, Credit-Card Spending (CCAvg), and Education, indicating that wealthier, higher-spending, and better-educated customers show the greatest likelihood of adopting new financial products .

4.2 Business Recommendations

  1. Target high-value segments focus future marketing on customers with above-average income and credit-card activity.
  2. Personalize loan messaging highlight flexible loan terms and loyalty benefits for graduate or professional customers to increase conversion.
  3. Use model outputs to prioritize outreach apply predicted probabilities to rank leads, directing sales resources to the top 1020 % most likely acceptors.
  4. Monitor over-exposure risk avoid redundant offers to customers already carrying large mortgages or debt balances, preserving satisfaction and compliance .

4.3 Caveats and Next Steps

  • Limitations: The model is trained on a single-bank dataset from one period; behavior may differ across regions or economic cycles. Random Forests complexity also limits interpretability for direct policy communication.
  • Risks: Potential over-reliance on income and spending could bias offers toward affluent groups; continuous fairness monitoring is required.
  • Next Steps:
    Perform cross-validation and hyper-parameter tuning (n_estimators, max_depth) to verify stability.
    Test additional ensemble algorithms such as Gradient Boosting or XGBoost for further lift.
    Incorporate behavioral or digital-channel data to enrich customer segmentation and reduce bias .
